\f0\b Context.
\f1\b0 \'a0Once an agent sees a lockbox metric, rank, or even pass/fail result, later ideas can adapt to it. Unlimited repeated queries eventually spend a fixed historical holdout.\

\f0\b Suggested answer.
\f1\b0 \'a0No. A sealed historical block may provide one-time campaign evidence, after which it is labeled spent/reused and counted in adaptive search. Only bars arriving after an exact row is frozen are untouched evidence for that row. Phase 1 may evaluate a formally reviewed reusable-holdout method, but Montauk should not assume one is needed.\

\f0\b Reasoning.
\f1\b0 \'a0This is the honest consequence of an always-on agent that learns from its failures.\

